1339":"1339","Lowther Castle, Askham, Westmorland, England":"Lowther Castle, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Cumbria, England":"Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lowther","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cumbria, so called from the river on which it stands. The placename is of obscure etymology, perhaps of ancient Welsh origin (compare   Lauder  ), or from Old Norse <i>lauthr</i> ‘froth, foam’ + <i>á</i> ‘river’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lawther","meanings":["Scottish, northern Irish, and northern English: variant of   Lowther   and   Lauder  ."]},{"name":"Lauder","meanings":["Scottish (Borders): habitational name from Lauder in Berwickshire, originally a name for the river Leader (itself from British <i>lou-</i> + <i>dubro-</i> ‘cleansing river’). Compare   Lauderdale  ."]},{"name":"Lattea","meanings":["Altered form of English   Lowther  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Hugh Lowther IV of Wythop was born in 1340, in Lowther, Westmorland, England, his father, Sir Hugh Lowther III, was 52 and his mother, Margaret De Lucy, was 65. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Quale. He died after 1373, in Lowther, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1340–1373 - +":"1340–pärast 1373","1307–1345":"1307–1345","1340–1373":"1340–1373","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1345–1373":"1345–1373","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1331–Female":"1331–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","–1380":"–1380","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1288–1367":"1288–1367","1275–1304":"1275–1304","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1373":"1373","1380":"1380","1304":"1304","1368":"1368","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1288":"1288","1430":"1430","1331":"1331","1373 - +":"pärast 1373","1307":"1307","1339":"1339","Lowther Castle, Askham, Westmorland, England":"Lowther Castle, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cumbria, England":"Cumbria, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1340–1373 - +":"1340–1373 jälkeen","1307–1345":"1307–1345","1340–1373":"1340–1373","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1345–1373":"1345–1373","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1331–Female":"1331–Kuollut","1339–Male":"1339–Kuollut","–1380":"–1380","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1288–1367":"1288–1367","1275–1304":"1275–1304","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1373":"1373","1380":"1380","1304":"1304","1368":"1368","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1288":"1288","1430":"1430","1331":"1331","1373 - +":"1373 jälkeen","1307":"1307","1339":"1339","Lowther Castle, Askham, Westmorland, England":"Lowther Castle, Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistyny